  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's inner-east has seen a significant increase in properties with secondary dwellings over the past decade. Whether it's a detached granny flat at the back of a Carina block, a dual occupancy in Morningside with separate street entries, or a converted garage in Norman Park operating as a rental, these properties present a distinct set of issues that don't arise in a standard single-dwelling sale. Sellers who understand these issues early get better outcomes. Those who discover them mid-campaign tend to lose buyers and time.</p>

      <p>The first thing to establish before listing is the approval status of the secondary dwelling. Brisbane City Council categorises secondary dwellings under the Brisbane City Plan, and the rules around what is permitted vary based on block size, zone, and when the structure was built. A structure that was built without a Development Approval, or that doesn't comply with the approval that was issued, creates a real problem for buyers who need finance. Lenders will flag unapproved structures during valuation, and the buyer's conveyancer will identify missing approvals when they search the title. Finding out your granny flat has no approval during a contract, rather than before you listed, is one of the more costly timing failures a seller can make.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Getting the approval paperwork right</h2>
      <p>If the secondary dwelling is fully approved and compliant, you should have copies of the Development Approval (DA), the Building Approval, and the Certificate of Classification or Final Inspection certificate. These should be provided to your selling agent before marketing begins, because buyers and their solicitors will ask for them. Having them ready demonstrates that the property is low-risk and makes the due diligence process faster and smoother for serious buyers.</p>

      <p>If you are not sure of the approval status, the best starting point is a search of Brisbane City Council's development and building records. Your conveyancer can assist with this, and a town planner can provide advice on whether any retrospective approvals or building certifications are obtainable if there are gaps. In some cases, retrospective certification is straightforward and adds material value. In others, the structure may need to be modified or removed to achieve compliance. Knowing which situation you are in before you list lets you make an informed decision about how to position and price the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How secondary dwellings affect valuation</h2>
      <p>A compliant, income-producing secondary dwelling adds genuine value in Brisbane, particularly where the rental market is tight. Buyers looking at inner-east suburbs are well aware that a granny flat generating $350 to $500 per week in rent materially changes the holding cost of a property. For owner-occupier buyers, this income can offset a significant portion of their mortgage repayments. For investor buyers, it represents a dual-income asset on a single land title, which is attractive for yield.</p>

      <p>However, the value add is not always as large as sellers expect, and it rarely translates dollar-for-dollar from the rental income to the sale price. A bank valuer will assess the secondary dwelling on the basis of comparable sales evidence and the income capitalisation method, constrained by what buyers in the area have actually paid for similar configurations. Your agent should be able to show you comparable sales that include secondary dwellings and explain the typical price premium buyers in your suburb are willing to pay, so your expectations are grounded in evidence rather than theory.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing tenants during the sale campaign</h2>
      <p>If the secondary dwelling is currently tenanted, you are selling a property subject to a residential tenancy agreement. Under Queensland tenancy law, you must give tenants proper notice before open homes and inspections, and they have legal rights that cannot be overridden by your desire to run an efficient campaign. The practical implications of this are significant: you cannot simply arrange open homes on whatever schedule suits you, and a tenant who is unhappy about the sale or uncooperative with access can materially slow your campaign.</p>

      <p>Managing this well starts before you list. A direct conversation with the tenant, explaining your intentions and what will be required of them during the campaign, costs nothing and often produces genuine cooperation. Tenants who understand the process and feel respected tend to be far more accommodating than those who first hear about the sale from a sign going up out front. Your property manager (if you have one) can assist with the formal notice requirements, and your selling agent should have experience navigating dual-occupancy tenant situations during campaigns.</p>

      <p>In some cases, sellers choose to wait until the tenancy has ended before listing, particularly if the tenancy is month-to-month and will expire soon, or if the relationship with the tenant is difficult. This is worth considering if the campaign timeline allows it, because an untenanted secondary dwelling is easier to present and easier for buyers to envision using as they choose.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Finding the right buyer pool</h2>
      <p>Properties with secondary dwellings attract a different buyer profile than standard single-dwelling homes. The primary buyer types are: owner-occupiers who want the rental income to help service a larger loan; extended families where the secondary dwelling provides independent living for an ageing parent or adult child; and investors focused on yield. Each of these buyers has different priorities, and effective marketing needs to speak to all three.</p>

      <p>The marketing approach should lead with the income potential and the compliance status, rather than treating the secondary dwelling as an afterthought. Floor plans for both dwellings, a clear explanation of the approval status, and accurate rental income figures (actual or market, clearly labelled) are all essential. Buyers considering a property of this type are making a more complex financial assessment than they would for a standard family home, and they need accurate information to move quickly and with confidence.</p>

      <p>The buyer pool for a well-presented, fully approved dual-income property in Brisbane's inner east is genuinely competitive. These properties do not sit on the market for long when they are correctly positioned, because the number of buyers who actively want this configuration reliably exceeds the supply of compliant, well-maintained examples.</p>

